## 1. Purpose
This policy defines how [COMPANY] uses cryptography to protect the confidentiality and integrity of PHI and other sensitive data at rest and in transit, and how cryptographic keys and secrets are managed across their lifecycle. Properly applied encryption also supports the HIPAA breach-notification **safe harbor** (`../healthcare/hipaa-breach-notification-procedure.md.template`).

## 2. Scope
Applies to all in-scope data stores and transport ([AWS] services, [Snowflake], [RDS], S3, application traffic, backups), all cryptographic keys and secrets used by [COMPANY] systems, and all workforce/automation that manages them. PHI is always classified as requiring encryption per `../asset-data/data-classification-and-handling.md.template`.

## 3. Policy
1. **All PHI and confidential data shall be encrypted at rest** using approved algorithms (§5) and keys managed per §6.
2. **All data in transit over untrusted networks shall be encrypted with TLS [1.2] or higher** (TLS 1.3 preferred); plaintext protocols (HTTP, FTP, unencrypted DB connections) **shall not** be used for PHI. Weak ciphers/protocols (SSLv3, TLS 1.0/1.1) **shall** be disabled.
3. Only **approved algorithms and key lengths** (§5) **shall** be used; deprecated/broken algorithms (MD5, SHA-1 for signatures, DES/3DES, RC4) **shall not** be used for protecting confidential data.
4. Cryptographic keys **shall** be generated, stored, rotated, revoked, and destroyed under a defined lifecycle (§6) using [AWS KMS] (or an approved HSM/KMS); private keys and symmetric keys **shall not** leave the boundary of the key store in plaintext.
5. **Secrets shall be stored in an approved secrets manager** ([AWS Secrets Manager] / [SSM Parameter Store, SecureString]) and retrieved at runtime; **secrets shall never be hardcoded** in source, IaC, container images, logs, or pipeline definitions (`secure-sdlc-policy.md.template`).
6. Access to keys and secrets **shall** follow least privilege via IAM/KMS key policies; key usage **shall** be logged (CloudTrail) and monitored (`logging-and-monitoring-policy.md.template`).
7. Keys **shall** be rotated on a defined schedule (§6) and immediately upon suspected compromise or workforce departure with access.
8. Cryptographic modules **shall** be FIPS 140-2/140-3 validated where required by contract or regulation [confirm requirement].

